WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.280 --> 00:00:10.690
[MUSIC]

2
00:00:10.690 --> 00:00:15.616
The composer, Claude Debussy, spent more
of his time in the company of poets and

3
00:00:15.616 --> 00:00:17.653
painters than he did musicians.

4
00:00:17.653 --> 00:00:22.477
His principal mentor was
the poet Stephane Mallarme

5
00:00:22.477 --> 00:00:27.628
who in 1876 penned a long
work in the symbolist style

6
00:00:27.628 --> 00:00:32.466
of poetry called the Afternoon of a Faun,
[FOREIGN].

7
00:00:32.466 --> 00:00:37.840
Well, the faun in this case is not
a young deer, but rather a sadder,

8
00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:43.494
a mythological beast half man,
usually the top half is man, half goat,

9
00:00:43.494 --> 00:00:50.880
who spends his days in the lustful pursuit
of the nymphs who inhabit the deep forest.

10
00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:54.050
Here are two images that
suggest the nature of the faun.

11
00:00:54.050 --> 00:00:59.706
Note on the left the pan pipes,
a rustic flute from Greek antiquity,

12
00:00:59.706 --> 00:01:02.400
that the faun plays.

13
00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:05.320
On this afternoon,
we see the faun, exhausted from

14
00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:10.067
the mornings escapades reclining in
the still air, of the midday heat.

15
00:01:11.172 --> 00:01:15.660
Now poem as we've said is
an example of symbolist poetry.

16
00:01:15.660 --> 00:01:20.760
The emphasis is not so much on a sequence
of sounds, that makes in tactical sense.

17
00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:26.500
But on setting a context in which
certain words stand out, pop out.

18
00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:29.490
And these words are frated
with special resonance.

19
00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:34.150
Just the sensuous sound of the word.

20
00:01:34.150 --> 00:01:39.250
And all of the associations that
come with this word in our mind,

21
00:01:39.250 --> 00:01:41.890
sounds and associations.

22
00:01:41.890 --> 00:01:44.550
That's what symbolist
poetry was all about and

23
00:01:44.550 --> 00:01:47.538
oddly that's exactly
what music is all about.

24
00:01:47.538 --> 00:01:51.660
Sounds and associations.

25
00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:57.311
Let me read just a short
passage of this 103 line poem.

26
00:01:57.311 --> 00:02:07.311
[FOREIGN].

27
00:02:29.693 --> 00:02:34.826
Well, let's hear what this
artificial puff of sound,

28
00:02:34.826 --> 00:02:37.564
sounds like on the keyboard.

29
00:02:37.564 --> 00:02:40.664
Let me play it for you.

30
00:02:40.664 --> 00:02:50.664
[MUSIC]

31
00:03:00.034 --> 00:03:02.332
And now, Debussy's score.

32
00:03:02.332 --> 00:03:06.745
And as we listen, I want you to tap
your foot to the music and conduct.

33
00:03:06.745 --> 00:03:09.893
Conduct in either two or three.

34
00:03:09.893 --> 00:03:10.869
Here we go.

