[MUSIC]

48
00:06:01.274 --> 00:06:03.884
Okay, that's the middle part and

49
00:06:03.884 --> 00:06:09.201
now the next slide will take us to
the conclusion of Debussy's piece.

50
00:06:09.201 --> 00:06:19.201
[MUSIC]

51
00:07:05.373 --> 00:07:08.937
Note that the music doesn't so
much end, climax.

52
00:07:08.937 --> 00:07:12.690
As it does sort of quietly and
very beautifully disappear.

53
00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:18.650
It's difficult to overestimate
the originality of this work by

54
00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:19.870
Claude Debussy.

55
00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:21.670
It was so different.

56
00:07:21.670 --> 00:07:24.650
Anything else that any composer
was creating at that time and

57
00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:28.750
certainly different from what
the Germans were creating at this time.

58
00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:32.940
As they say, this piece by Debussy
is completely outside the box and

59
00:07:32.940 --> 00:07:38.060
it changed the nature of what
the western musical box sounded like.

60
00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:43.300
Opening our ears to new sounds,
new chords and new scales.

61
00:07:44.550 --> 00:07:47.860
But by way of review,
let's just reprise what we've learned so

62
00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:50.270
far about Debussy's Afternoon of a Faun.

63
00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:52.540
Again, the beat is suppressed.

64
00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:55.240
This is not foot stomping music here.

65
00:07:56.310 --> 00:07:59.605
To say that there's no melody,
well that's a bit of an exaggeration.

66
00:07:59.605 --> 00:08:06.392
Maybe closer to mark to say
that we hear here flourishes.

67
00:08:06.392 --> 00:08:09.380
Arabesque, Phillips of sound if you will.

68
00:08:09.380 --> 00:08:15.530
But not melody as we traditionally known,
traditionally understood it.

69
00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:17.900
And of course we have this
new found importance.

70
00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:24.780
This new found sense of color splotches or
dabs of color in the orchestra.

71
00:08:24.780 --> 00:08:27.700
The musical form however is traditional.

72
00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:29.870
Traditional ternary ABA.

73
00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:34.190
Indeed, that's true of Debussy's Clair
de Lune that we heard earlier as well.

74
00:08:34.190 --> 00:08:36.680
New sounds but traditional form.

75
00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:42.490
At the time of the first performance of
the Prelude to The Afternoon of a Faun,

76
00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:44.740
Debussy said the following
about the piece.

77
00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:49.000
Quote, my prelude is really
a sequence of mood paintings,

78
00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:50.820
throughout which the desire and

79
00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:56.330
the dreams of the fallen move in
the heat of the midday sun, end quote.

80
00:08:56.330 --> 00:08:58.850
And when the poet
Mallarme heard the music,

81
00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:03.190
he in turn said the following
about Debussy's music, quote,

82
00:09:03.190 --> 00:09:08.390
I never expected anything like it, the
music prolongs the emotion of my poem and

83
00:09:08.390 --> 00:09:11.730
paints its scenery more
passionately than could colors.

84
